Ziya is a self-hosted AI workbench that runs alongside your editor rather than
replacing it. You point it at a codebase, run it locally, and talk to it in a
browser or terminal. It started about two years ago as a small project to put a
usable frontend on AWS Bedrock and fix the things that were frustrating about
other AI tools at the time — auto-compaction throwing away the parts of a
conversation that mattered, copy-paste-from-chat as the primary diff workflow,
visual output treated as a niche concern. It's been mine to evolve for the last
year and a half, and is now used daily by a few hundred engineers at a large
company.

The shape of it:

- Diffs come back rendered with per-hunk Apply/Undo. A four-stage patch pipeline
  handles the not-quite-right output models produce; a regression suite of
  ~345 awkward patches keeps it honest.
- Context is user-controlled. No auto-compaction. Mute, fork, truncate, drop
  files. 30+ turn sessions are normal.
- Inline visualizations through seven renderers (Mermaid, Graphviz, Vega-Lite,
  DrawIO, KaTeX, HTML mockups, packet diagrams) — the model picks the format.
- MCP tool integration with HMAC-signed results, fabrication detection in the
  text stream, and a three-strike kill on hallucinated tool calls.
- AST-indexed code intelligence with reference tracing, importer/caller queries,
  and symbol search.
- Parallel agent swarms with dependency ordering, memory crystals, and
  crash-resilient checkpointing — useful when work is genuinely parallel.
- Same backend in browser UI and CLI (`ziya chat`, `ziya ask`, `ziya review`).
- Multiple model providers (Bedrock, Google, OpenAI, Anthropic) with mid-
  conversation switching for second opinions and rate-limit routing.

Self-hosted, MIT licensed, no telemetry, no account.

It is not an IDE and isn't trying to become one. If your workflow moves between
code, architecture, operational data, and visual debugging across many threads
and you find that existing AI tools cover only part of that surface, this is
the kind of thing that's worth twenty minutes of your time.